A student working with the following three vectors in \complex{3},
\vect{x} &= \begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\-1\end{bmatrix}& \vect{y} &= \begin{bmatrix}3\\1\\1\end{bmatrix}& \vect{z} &= \begin{bmatrix}5\\-5\\7 \end{bmatrix}
showed that 4\vect{x} - 3\vect{y} + \vect{z} = \zerovector. What conclusion can the student draw about the set \set{\vect{x}, \vect{y}, \vect{z}} and why?

The set S is
                    S = \left \{ \colvector{ 1\\1\\3 },\, \colvector{ 2\\1\\1},\, \vect{w} \right\}
                where \vect{w} is given below.  Determine whether S is linearly independent for the given \vect{w} then drag \vect{w} onto one of three results.

Suppose that the set
\{\vect{u},\,\vect{v},\,\vect{w}\}
is linearly independent.  Is the set
\{\vect{u} + \vect{v},\,\vect{u} + \vect{w},\, \vect{v} + \vect{w}\}
linearly independent? Why or why not?

solution.p:
With three vectors from \complex{3}, we can form a square matrix by making these three vectors the columns of a matrix.  We do so, and row-reduce to obtain\begin{bmatrix}
                    \leading{1} & 0 & 0\\
                    0 & \leading{1} & 0\\
                    0 & 0 & \leading{1}
                    \end{bmatrix}the 3\times 3 identity matrix.  So by  the original matrix is nonsingular and its columns are therefore a linearly independent set.

