statement.p:
For the matrix A below, find a set of vectors S so that (1) S is linearly independent, and (2) the span of S equals the null space of A, \spn{S}=\nsp{A}.  (See .)A=
                \begin{bmatrix}
                1 & 1 & 6 & -8\\
                1 & -2 & 0 & 1\\
                -2 & 1 & -6 & 7
                \end{bmatrix}

Consider the subspace W=\spn{\set{\vect{v}_1,\,\vect{v}_2,\,\vect{v}_3,\,\vect{v}_4}}.  Find a set S so that (1)  S is a subset of W, (2) S is linearly independent, and (3) W=\spn{S}.  Write each vector not included in S as a linear combination of the vectors that are in S.
                    \vect{v}_1&=\colvector{1\\-1\\2}
                    &
                    \vect{v}_2&=\colvector{4\\-4\\8}
                    &
                    \vect{v}_3&=\colvector{-3\\2\\-7}
                    &
                    \vect{v}_4&=\colvector{2\\1\\7}

solution.p:
Then
                    \vect{v}_2&=4\vect{v_1}+0\vect{v_3}
                    &
                    \vect{v}_4&=-7\vect{v_1}-3\vect{v_3}
                The two equations above are enough to justify the set equality
                    W
                    &=\spn{\set{\vect{v}_1,\,\vect{v}_2,\,\vect{v}_3,\,\vect{v}_4}}
                    =\spn{\set{\vect{v}_1,\,\vect{v}_3}}
                    =\spn{S}
                There are other solutions (for example, swap the roles of \vect{v}_1 and \vect{v}_2, but by upcoming theorems we can confidently claim that any solution will be a set S with exactly two vectors.

